1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,500
Hello, and welcome to this compliance review screencast for Verdent —
a YouTube video search and analysis tool.

2
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:16,000
Verdent is built on top of the YouTube Data API v3.
This recording demonstrates how our application accesses and displays YouTube API data.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:24,000
This demonstrates compliance with YouTube's API Services Terms of Service
and Developer Policies.

4
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:35,000
Verdent is a single-page web application served by a FastAPI back-end.
Users can search for YouTube videos by keyword and apply various filters.

5
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Available filters include: video duration, publication date,
category, language, and region.

6
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:54,000
All data displayed in this application comes exclusively from
the YouTube Data API v3. No data is scraped.

7
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Let me demonstrate a live search.
I'll type the keyword "gaming" and hit Search.

8
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:15,000
The application calls the YouTube Data API search.list endpoint
with the keyword, video type, duration filter, and region code.

9
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:25,000
The search.list call consumes 100 quota units.
Results are ordered by view count.

10
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:35,000
The back-end then calls videos.list in batches of up to 50 IDs,
consuming only 1 quota unit per batch.

11
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:45,000
This retrieves full statistics for each video:
views, likes, comments, and duration.

12
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:58,000
The results are now displayed.
Each card shows the thumbnail, title, channel name, and key metrics.

13
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:10,000
For every video in the top-10 results, Verdent displays data
sourced directly from the YouTube Data API.

14
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Thumbnail: from snippet.thumbnails.
Title: from snippet.title.
Channel: from snippet.channelTitle.

15
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Subscriber count: from channels.list using statistics.subscriberCount.
View count: from statistics.viewCount.

16
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:42,000
Engagement Rate (ENG%) is calculated as viewCount divided by subscriberCount,
showing how well the video performs relative to the channel's audience.

17
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:53,000
Estimated Revenue is derived from industry-standard CPM ranges,
presented as a reference estimate only.

18
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:05,000
The trend analysis graphs visualise the distribution of views,
engagement rates, and publication dates across the result set.

19
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:15,000
All of this data is presented in real time from the API response.
No data is permanently stored in a database.

20
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:28,000
Let me highlight the API call optimisation built into the application.
First: quota awareness.

21
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:40,000
Each search.list call costs 100 units.
Each videos.list call costs 1 unit per batch of up to 50 videos.

22
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:52,000
The daily quota limit of 10,000 units is respected and monitored
via the /api/quota endpoint.

23
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:04,000
Second: server-side caching.
Results are cached for 30 minutes using an in-memory cache.

24
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:14,000
If the same search is repeated within 30 minutes,
the cached response is served immediately — zero additional API calls.

25
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:26,000
This dramatically reduces quota consumption for repeated queries.
Watch — the second search completes instantly.

26
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:38,000
Third: API key rotation.
If one key's quota is exhausted, the client rotates to the next key automatically.

27
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:50,000
This ensures uninterrupted service without manual intervention.

28
00:04:50,000 --> 00:05:02,000
Every video result includes a direct link back to the original video on YouTube,
ensuring users can always access the authoritative source.

29
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:14,000
Channel information — subscriber counts and recent uploads —
is also obtained via the YouTube Data API channels.list endpoint.

30
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:26,000
Channel data is similarly cached for 30 minutes
to minimise redundant API calls.

31
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:38,000
Verdent helps content creators and marketers with market research,
identifying high-performing videos in any niche.

32
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:50,000
Revenue estimation: gauge monetisation potential based on engagement data.
Competitive analysis: compare channel performance across creators.

33
00:05:50,000 --> 00:06:02,000
Trend identification: spot patterns in publication timing
and view velocity across search results.

34
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:15,000
All use cases rely solely on public data available
through the YouTube Data API v3.

35
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:28,000
In summary: we only call the YouTube Data API through official REST endpoints.
We do not scrape or redistribute raw API data.

36
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:40,000
All data is displayed in an aggregated, analytical context —
not as a substitute for YouTube.

37
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:52,000
Every video and channel links back to YouTube.
Quota usage is tracked, capped, and minimised through caching and batching.

38
00:06:52,000 --> 00:07:05,000
Thank you for reviewing Verdent's YouTube API Services
compliance demonstration.

39
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:20,000
This concludes the Verdent compliance screencast.
For questions regarding API usage, please refer to the project repository.
